# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fedora-linux
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] The DNF package manager works similarly to other package managers.
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] Its core usage works very similarly to the Apt Package Manager, such as `install`, `remove`, and `upgrade`.
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] Perceived deficiencies of yum (which DNF is intended to address) include poor performance, high memory usage, and the slowness of its iterative dependency resolution.
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] DNF uses libsolv, an external dependency resolver (developed by openSUSE).
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] DNF was originally written in Python, but in 2016, efforts were under way to port it to C and move most functionality from Python code into the new libdnf library.
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] In 2018, the DNF team announced the decision to move libdnf from C to C++. libdnf is already used by PackageKit, a Linux distribution-agnostic package system abstraction library, even though the library doesn't have most of DNF's features.
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] Since the launch of Fedora Linux 41, DNF5 is the new default packaging tool.
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] This release features new performance enhancements, updated terminal output, and fully integrated modularity.
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] DNF has been the default command-line package manager for Fedora since version 22, which was released in May 2015.
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] The libdnf library is used as a package backend in PackageKit, which offers a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] Later, dnfdragora was developed for Fedora 27 as another alternative graphical front-end of DNF.
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] DNF has also been available as an alternate package manager for Mageia Linux since version 6 and may become the default sometime in the future.
[src:fedora-linux/dnf-software] In Red Hat Enterprise Linux, and by extension, AlmaLinux and Rocky Linux, yum is an alias for dnf.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Since the release of Fedora 21 in December 2014, three editions have been made available: personal computer, server and cloud computing.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] This was expanded to five editions for containerization and Internet of Things (IoT) as of the release of Fedora 37 in November 2022.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] A new version of Fedora Linux is released every six months.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] As of February 2016, Fedora Linux has an estimated 1.2 million users, including Linus Torvalds, creator of the Linux kernel (as of November 2025).
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora has a reputation for focusing on innovation, integrating new technologies early on and working closely with upstream Linux communities.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Making changes upstream instead of specifically for Fedora Linux ensures that the changes are available to all Linux distributions.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora Linux has a relatively short life cycle: Each version is usually supported for at least 13 months, where version *X* is supported only until one month after version *X*+2 is released and with approximately six months between most versions.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora users can upgrade from version to version without reinstalling.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The default desktop environment is GNOME, and the default user interface is the GNOME Shell.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Other desktop environments are available, including KDE Plasma, COSMIC, Xfce, LXQt, LXDE, MATE, Cinnamon, and Budgie as well as window managers including i3, Sway, and Miracle.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] A live media drive can be created using Fedora Media Writer, the official bootable USB creator for Fedora Linux, or the dd command, allowing users to try Fedora Linux without writing any changes to their hard drives.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Most Fedora Linux editions use the RPM package management system and DNF as a tool to manage installed software.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] DNF uses libsolv, an external dependency resolver.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The CoreOS and Silverblue editions are designed for operating system-level virtualization.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] These editions use rpm-ostree (a hybrid transactional image/package system), and traditional RPM (or other package management systems) can be used in containers.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora Linux uses Security-Enhanced Linux by default, which implements a variety of security policies, including mandatory access controls, which Fedora adopted early on.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora provides a hardening wrapper, and does hardening for all of its packages by using compiler features such as position-independent executable (PIE).
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora also ships with firewalld as a default firewall.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora Workstation comes preinstalled with a wide range of software such as LibreOffice and Firefox.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Additional software is available from the software repositories and can be installed using the DNF package manager or GNOME Software.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Additionally, extra repositories can be added to the system, so that software not available in Fedora Linux can be installed easily.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Software that is not available via official Fedora repositories, either because it does not meet Fedora's definition of free software or because its distribution may violate US law, can be installed using third-party repositories.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Popular third-party repositories include RPM Fusion free and non-free repositories.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora also provides users with an easy-to-use build system for creating their own repositories called Copr.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Since the release of Fedora 25, the operating system defaults to the Wayland display server protocol, which replaced the X Window System.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] As of Fedora 41, both the GNOME and KDE editions do not ship with X.Org Server session support by default.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Beginning with Fedora 21, the distribution was available in three editions, expanded to six editions as of version 42.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The Fedora Workstation editions target users who want a reliable, user-friendly, and powerful operating system for their laptop or desktop computer while still being on the cutting edge of new technologies.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] They come with GNOME by default but other desktops can be installed, including KDE Plasma, which was promoted to a regular edition on the same level as Fedora Workstation with GNOME starting with Fedora 42.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The Fedora project officially distributes different variations called "Fedora Spins" which are Fedora Linux with different desktop environments.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The current official spins, as of Fedora 44, are Xfce, LXQt, MATE (with Compiz), Cinnamon, LXDE, SoaS, i3, KDE Plasma Mobile, Budgie, Sway, Miracle, and COSMIC.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] In addition to Spins, which are official variants of the Fedora system, the project allows unofficial variants to use the term "Fedora Remix" without asking for further permission, although a different logo (provided) is required.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora offers immutable editions known as "Atomic Desktops".
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Separate editions are offered per desktop environment, currently there are editions for Budgie, COSMIC, GNOME (Silverblue), KDE Plasma (Kinoite) and Sway.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Every atomic desktop installation is identical to every other installation of the same version, and it never changes as it is used.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The immutable design is intended to make the operating system more stable, less prone to bugs, easier to test and develop, and create a platform for containerized applications as well as container-based software development.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Applications and containers are kept separate from the host system.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] OS updates are fast and there is no installation stage.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] It is possible to roll back to the previous version of the operating system, if something goes wrong.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The long-term goal for this effort is to transform Fedora Workstation into an image-based system where applications are separate from the OS, and updates are atomic.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora developers, Red Hat engineers, along with independent contributors have been developing or contributing to software used in the atomic desktops such as OSTree, Wayland, Flatpak, and rpm-ostree support in GNOME Software, etc.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Project Atomic added new features like package layering to rpm-ostree and added rpm-ostree support to Anaconda.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] It includes the latest data center technologies.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] This edition does not come with a desktop environment, but one can be installed.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] From Fedora 28, Server Edition will deliver Fedora Modularity, adding support for alternative update streams for popular software such as Node.js and Go.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Images of Fedora Linux tailored to running on Internet of Things devices.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] It supports x86_64, aarch64 and armhfp processors.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The successor of *Fedora Atomic Host* (Project Atomic) and Container Linux after Fedora 29, it provides a minimal image of Fedora Linux which includes just the bare essentials.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] This is not to be confused with Fedora Core.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] It is meant for deployment in cloud computing.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] It provides Fedora CoreOS images which are optimized minimal images for deploying containers.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] CoreOS replaced the established Container Linux when it was merged with Project Atomic after its acquisition by Red Hat in January 2018.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Similar to Debian blends, the Fedora Project also distributes custom variations of Fedora Linux called Fedora Labs.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] These are built with specific sets of software packages, targeting specific interests such as gaming, security, design, robotics, and scientific computing (that includes SciPy, Octave, Kile, Xfig and Inkscape).
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The Fedora AOS (Appliance Operating System) was a specialized spin of Fedora Linux with reduced memory footprint for use in software appliances.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Appliances are pre-installed, pre-configured, system images.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] This spin was intended to make it easier for anyone (developers, independent software vendors (ISV), original equipment manufacturers (OEM), etc.) to create and deploy virtual appliances.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] x86-64 and ARM AArch64 are the primary architectures supported by Fedora.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] As of release 38, Fedora also supports IBM Power64le, IBM Z ("s390x"), MIPS-64el, MIPS-el and RISC-V as secondary architectures.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora 28 was the last release that supported ppc64 and users are advised to move to the little endian ppc64le variant.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora 36 was the last release with support for ARM-hfp.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The Fedora Project also distributes several other versions with fewer use cases than mentioned above, like network installers and minimal installation images.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] They are intended for special cases or expert users that want to have custom installations or configuring Fedora from scratch.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] In addition, all acceptable licenses for Fedora Linux (including copyright, trademark, and patent licenses) must be applicable not only to Red Hat or Fedora, but also to all recipients downstream.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] This means that any "Fedora-only" licenses, or licenses with specific terms that Red Hat or Fedora meets but that other recipients would not are not acceptable (and almost certainly non-free, as a result).
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The name of Fedora derives from the original "Fedora Linux", a volunteer project that provided extra software for the Red Hat Linux distribution, and from the characteristic fedora hat used in Red Hat's "Shadowman" logo.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Warren Togami began Fedora Linux in 2002 as an undergraduate project at the University of Hawaii, intended to provide a single repository for well-tested third-party software packages so that non-Red Hat software would be easier to find, develop, and use.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The key difference between Fedora Linux and Red Hat Linux was that Fedora's repository development would be collaborative with the global volunteer community.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The original Fedora Linux was eventually absorbed into the Fedora Project, carrying with it this collaborative approach.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The Fedora Project is sponsored primarily by Red Hat with additional support and sponsors from other companies and organizations.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] In 2003, Fedora Linux and Red Hat Linux merged to create the Fedora Project and its distribution, Fedora Core.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The Red Hat Linux product was discontinued so the team could focus on their paid version for servers: Red Hat Enterprise Linux.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux was to be Red Hat's only officially supported Linux distribution, while Fedora was to be a community distribution.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Red Hat Enterprise Linux branches its releases from versions of Fedora.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Before Fedora 7, Fedora Linux was called Fedora Core after the name of one of the two main software repositories - Core and Extras.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora Core contained all the base packages that were required by the operating system, as well as other packages that were distributed along with the installation media, and was maintained only by Red Hat developers.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora Extras, the secondary repository that had been included since Fedora Core 3, was community-maintained and not distributed along with the installation media.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Upon the release of Fedora 7, the distinction between Fedora Core and Fedora Extras was eliminated.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Red Hat's application for trademark status for the name "Fedora" was disputed by Cornell University and the University of Virginia Library, creators of the unrelated Fedora Commons digital repository management software.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] In April 2020, project leader Matthew Miller announced that Fedora Workstation would be shipping on select new ThinkPad laptops, thanks to a new partnership with Lenovo.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Framework officially supports Fedora Workstation on their laptops.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Development of the operating system and supporting programs is headed by the Fedora Project, which is composed of a community of developers and volunteers, and also Red Hat employees.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The council is the top-level community leadership and governance body.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] On July 2024, Fedora released a survey to its users on what they thought about introducing AI technologies into Fedora.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Despite the survey announcer Aoife Moloney wanting to "keep the tone of this survey positive about AI", data scientist Greg Sutcliffe found that "'no' is pretty much the largest category in every case" on using AI on tasks in Fedora, with a strong rejection on AI usage overall.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Despite that, a draft policy for AI policy was published on September 22, 2025 and was approved a month later on October 22, 2025.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] In 2026, a proposal to make a variant of Fedora specifically for AI was made.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The proposal was set up so that changes in the Fedora Project would make it easier for creation of the Fedora AI variant, including the setup of a LTS kernel on Fedora.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] As a result of the discussion; Fernando Mancera, a "long-time" Fedora Contributor, left the Fedora Project.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The Fedora AI proposal was unanimously approved on May 6, though stalled two days later after two council members changed their vote after significant community backlash over the proposal.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] On May 14, Miro Hrončok posted his vote to reject the proposal*,* after concerns were raised to him after the initial vote that the Fedora community was "not supportive of this initiative as is".
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Fedora has a relatively short life cycle: version *X* is supported only until 1 month after version *X*+2 is released and with approximately 6 months between most versions, meaning a version of Fedora is usually supported for at least 13 months, possibly longer.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] The current release is Fedora 44, which was released on 28 April 2026.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Rawhide is the development tree for Fedora.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] This is a copy of a complete Fedora distribution where new software is added and tested, before inclusion in a later stable release.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] As such, Rawhide is often more feature rich than the current stable release.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] In many cases, the software is made of CVS, Subversion or Git source code snapshots which are often actively developed by programmers.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Although Rawhide is targeted at advanced users, testers, and package maintainers, it is capable of being a primary operating system.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Users interested in the Rawhide branch often update on a daily basis and help troubleshoot problems.
[src:fedora-linux/fedora-linux] Rawhide users do not have to upgrade between different versions as it follows a rolling release update model.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME is developed by the GNOME Project, which is composed of both volunteers and paid contributors, the largest corporate contributor being Red Hat.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] It is an international project that aims to develop frameworks for software development, to program end-user applications based on these frameworks, and to coordinate efforts for the internationalization, localization, and accessibility of that software.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] In 2023 and 2024, GNOME received €1,000,000 from Germany's Sovereign Tech Fund.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Since GNOME 2, productivity has been a key focus for GNOME.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] To meet this end, the GNOME Human Interface Guidelines (HIG) were created.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] All GNOME programs share a coherent style of interfaces but are not limited to the employment of the same GUI widgets.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Rather, the design of the GNOME's interface is guided by concepts described in the HIG, itself relying on insights from cognitive ergonomics.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Following the HIG, developers can create high-quality, consistent, and usable GUI programs, as it addresses everything from interface design to the recommended pixel-based layout of widgets.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] However, critics have complained about GNOME ignoring traditional user interface conventions, and the wasting of screen real estate.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] During the GNOME 2 rewrite, many settings deemed of little value to the majority of users were removed.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME aims to make and keep the desktop environment physically and cognitively ergonomic for people with disabilities.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The GNOME Human Interface Guidelines try to take this into account as far as possible but specific issues are solved by special software.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME addresses computer accessibility issues by using the Accessibility Toolkit (ATK) application programming interface, which allows enhancing user experience by using special input methods and speech synthesis and speech recognition software.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Particular utilities are registered with ATK using Assistive Technology Service Provider Interface (AT-SPI), and become globally used throughout the desktop.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Several assistive technology providers, including Orca screen reader and Dasher input method, were developed specifically for use with GNOME.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The internationalization and localization of GNOME software relies on locale, and supports 197 languages with varying levels of completion, with some not being translated at all.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME Shell is the main graphical shell of GNOME.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] It features a top bar holding (from left to right) an Overview button, a clock and an integrated system status menu.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The application menu displays the name of the application in focus and provides access to functions such as accessing the application's preferences, closing the application, or creating a new application window.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The status menu holds various system status indicators, shortcuts to system settings, and session actions including logging out, switching users, locking the screen, and suspending the computer.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Clicking on the Activities button, moving the mouse to the top-left hot corner or pressing the Super key brings up the Overview.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The Overview gives users an overview of current activities and provides a way to switch between windows and workspaces and to launch applications.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The Dash on the bottom houses shortcuts to favorite applications, currently open windows, and an application picker button to show a list of all installed applications.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] A search bar appears at the top and a workspace list for viewing and switching between workspaces is directly above it.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Notifications appear from the top of the shell.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME Classic also adds the minimize and maximize buttons to window headers.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] There are a large number of GTK-based programs written by various authors.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Since the release of GNOME 3.0, GNOME Project concentrates on developing a set of programs that accounts for the GNOME Core Applications.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The commonalities of the GNOME Core Applications are the adherence to the current GNOME Human Interface Guidelines (HIG) as well as the tight integration with underlying GNOME layers like e.g.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GVfs (GNOME virtual filesystem) and also with one another e.g.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GOA (gnome-online-accounts) settings and GNOME Files with Google Drive and GNOME Photos with Google Photos.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Some programs are simply existing programs with a new name and revamped user interface, while others have been written from scratch.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The GNOME project provides a suite of software development tools to facilitate the creation of GNOME software.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] These tools are designed to streamline the development process for the GNOME ecosystem.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] These tools collectively provide a comprehensive development environment for creating software that aligns with the GNOME desktop and its design principles.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME Circle is a collection of applications which have been built to extend the GNOME platform, utilize GNOME technologies, and follow the GNOME human interface guidelines.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME was started on 15 August 1997 by Miguel de Icaza and Federico Mena as a free software project to develop a desktop environment and applications for it.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] It was founded in part because the K Desktop Environment, which was growing in popularity, relied on the Qt widget toolkit which used a proprietary software license until version 2.0 (June 1999).
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] In place of Qt, GTK (formerly called GIMP Toolkit) was chosen as the base of GNOME.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GTK is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL), a free software license that allows software linking to it to use a much wider set of licenses, including proprietary software licenses.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME itself is licensed under the LGPL for its libraries and the GNU General Public License (GPL) for its applications.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME was formerly a part of the GNU Project, but that is no longer the case.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] In 2021, GNOME Executive Director Neil McGovern publicly tweeted that GNOME was not a GNU project and that he had been asking GNU to remove GNOME from their list of packages since 2019.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] In 2021, GNOME was removed from the list.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME proceeded to remove mentions of any link to GNU from their code and documentation.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The name "GNOME" was initially an acronym for *GNU Network Object Model Environment*, referring to the original intention of creating a distributed object framework similar to Microsoft's OLE, but the acronym was eventually dropped because it no longer reflected the vision of the GNOME project.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The California startup Eazel developed the Nautilus file manager from 1999 to 2001.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] De Icaza and Nat Friedman founded Helix Code (later Ximian) in 1999 in Massachusetts; this company developed GNOME's infrastructure and applications and was purchased by Novell in 2003.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] During the transition to GNOME 2 and shortly thereafter, there were brief talks about creating a *GNOME Office* suite.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] On 15 September 2003 GNOME-Office 1.0, consisting of AbiWord 2.0, GNOME-DB 1.0, and Gnumeric 1.2.0, was released.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Although some release planning for GNOME Office 1.2 was happening on the gnome-office mailing list, and Gnumeric 1.4 was announced as a part of it, the 1.2 release of the suite itself never materialized.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] As of 4 May 2014, the GNOME wiki only mentions "GNOME/GTK applications that are useful in an office environment".
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 2 was released in June 2002 and was very similar to a conventional desktop interface, featuring a simple desktop in which users could interact with virtual objects such as windows, icons, and files.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 2 started out with Sawfish as its default window manager, but later switched to Metacity in GNOME 2.2.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The handling of windows, applications, and files in GNOME 2 is similar to that of contemporary desktop operating systems.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] However, these features can be moved to almost any position or orientation the user desires, replaced with other functions, or removed altogether.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] As of 2009, GNOME 2 was the default desktop for OpenSolaris.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] In 2008, an increasing discontent among the community and developers about the lack of project direction and technical progress prompted the announcement of GNOME 3.0.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Originally, the plan was to make only incremental changes and avoid disruption for users.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] This changed when efforts led to the creation of the GNOME Shell.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 3 brought many enhancements to core software.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Many GNOME Core Applications also went through redesigns to provide a better user experience.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Mutter replaced Metacity as the default window manager, and Adwaita replaced Clearlooks as the default theme.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The release of GNOME 3 caused considerable controversy in the GNU and Linux communities.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Aiming to provide an easy-to-use and uncluttered user experience has led to some criticized design decisions, like the removal of *minimize* and *maximize* buttons, the simplification of configuration options, and visual cues that could lead to confusion.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Among those critical of the early releases of GNOME 3 is Linus Torvalds, the creator of the Linux kernel.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Torvalds abandoned GNOME for a while after the release of GNOME 3.0, saying, "The developers have apparently decided that it's 'too complicated' to actually do real work on your desktop, and have decided to make it really annoying to do".
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Over time, critical reception has grown more positive.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] In 2013, Torvalds resumed using GNOME, noting that "they have extensions now that are still much too hard to find; but with extensions you can make your desktop look almost as good as it used to look two years ago".
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Debian, a Linux distribution that had historically used GNOME 2, switched to Xfce when GNOME 3 was released, but re-adopted GNOME 3 in time for the release of Debian 8 "Jessie".
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Ubuntu switched from Unity to GNOME 3 with several extensions to resemble Unity, such as a persistent left application panel instead of a hidden dock and re-enabling desktop icons, with Ubuntu 17.10 Artful Aardvark in 2017.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] This release also saw the Ubuntu GNOME edition merge with the mainline release.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] However, Ubuntu Unity was then released, keeping the Unity desktop and continuing to update it.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] It immediately follows version 3, but adopts a new versioning scheme and a schedule of future major releases on a fixed six-month cycle (see Release Cycle).
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] With this quicker release cadence, major releases became somewhat leaner, because full rewrites of major packages were not occurring as often as they were in the jumps between GNOME 1.0, 2.0, and 3.0 versions.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 40 organizes the activities overview in a horizontal fashion, instead of using a vertical design like its predecessors.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The release also brings new touchpad gestures.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 42 was released on 23 March 2022 and introduced the option to screen record and switch light/dark themes using a new GTK API called Libadwaita.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Several default apps were replaced with more modern versions such as Text Editor instead of Gedit and Console instead of Terminal.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 43 (Guadalajara) was released on 21 September 2022 and introduced a new quick settings menu, a GNOME Files update to GTK4, and a new 'Device Security' panel in settings, among many other changes.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME Web was updated, bringing in support for web apps and experimental Firefox and Chrome extension support.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 44 (Kuala Lumpur) was released on 22 March 2023.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Named after Kuala Lumpur in recognition of work done by the GNOME.Asia community, GNOME 44 introduced a new file chooser grid view, updated settings panels, and redesigned accessibility settings.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The new quick settings menu introduced in GNOME 43 was updated, alongside the addition of several new apps and improvements to existing apps.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 45 (Rīga) was released on 20 September 2023.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] It introduced redesigned app styles alongside a new activities button, which replaced both the previous "Activities" label and the app menu with a graphical workspace indicator.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Other updates to the system bar included a new camera usage indicator and a keyboard shortcut to open and close the quick settings menu.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 45 also introduced two new image viewer and camera apps, keyboard backlight controls, and numerous enhancements to existing apps.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 46 (Kathmandu) was released on 20 March 2024 and featured an enhanced files app with global search, support for headless remote login via GDM, and a refreshed settings app, amongst many other app changes.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Other system changes included accessibility improvements and experimental support for variable refresh rates.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 47 (Denver) was released on 18 September 2024 and introduced support for user-selected accent colors in Libadwaita applications, allowing greater interface customization.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] It also brought improvements for low-resolution displays through automatic icon scaling, optimizations in screen recording with GPU hardware encoding, and various enhancements to performance, file navigation, and online accounts.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 48 (Bengaluru) was released on 19 March 2025 and is included in Fedora 42 and Ubuntu 25.04.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] This version introduced notification grouping by application (notification stacking), significant performance improvements such as dynamic triple buffering for smoother animations, and optimizations in CPU and memory usage across key system components.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] It also included improvements in file indexing and graphical stability on systems with dedicated GPUs.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 49 (Brescia) was released in September 2025 and is included in Fedora 43 and Ubuntu 25.10.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] It deprecated X11 support, disabling it by default.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] It also replaced the video player Totem and the document viewer Evince with Showtime and Papers, respectively, and introduced shutting down and restarting the computer when logged out.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 50 (Tokyo) was released on 18 March 2026.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 50 removed X11 support from the source code.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] It introduced new parental control features, accessibility improvements such as global options and reduced animations, and optimizations in core applications such as Files (Nautilus) and Calendar.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] It also added improvements to remote desktop with hardware acceleration, expanded graphics support (including enhancements for NVIDIA and variable refresh rates), and new options in system settings.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] By default, GNOME Flashback contains two panels (one on the top, and one to its opposite on the bottom) spanning the width of the screen.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The top panel usually contains navigation menus labeled "Applications" and "Places" in that order, as the "System" menu from GNOME 2.x has been replaced by a control panel in GNOME 3.x.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] These menus hold links to common applications and areas of the file system, respectively.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] A user menu placed on the opposite side of the screen, which has been available since GNOME 2.14 but has become more prominent in GNOME 3.x, holds access to account and system settings as well as options to log out, switch user, and shut down the computer.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The top panel usually contains a clock/calendar and a notification area, which can double as a sort of dock, as well.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The bottom panel is commonly empty by default (other than a set of buttons to navigate between desktops) due to its use in the navigation between windows (windows minimize to the bottom panel by default).
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Users can populate these panels with other completely customizable menus and buttons, including new menus, search boxes, and icons, with the icons in particular (called *launchers*) performing functions similar to the *quick-launch* feature found in the Microsoft Windows 98–Vista taskbar.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Other applications can also be attached to the panels, and the panels are highly reconfigurable: anything on these panels can be moved, removed, or configured in other ways.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The version of GNOME Panel available in the repository for Ubuntu 12.04 offers a modified version of Fallback Mode with the addition of a custom theme and ports of Ubuntu's own Indicators from their old GNOME 2.x desktop.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Trisquel uses Fallback Mode (Flashback) for its main desktop, because GNOME Shell requires 3D acceleration as it relies on graphics composition, while some free software drivers do not support 3D acceleration, among other reasons like more usability and more stability.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Each of the component software products in the GNOME project has its own version number and release schedule.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] However, individual module maintainers coordinate their efforts to create a full GNOME stable release on an approximately six-month schedule, alongside its underlying libraries such as GTK and GLib.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Some experimental projects are excluded from these releases.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Before GNOME 40, GNOME version numbers followed the scheme *v.xx.yy*.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Here, *v* is a major version, which can include large changes such as ABI breakage; these have no regular schedule and occur in response to requirements for large-scale changes.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] *xx* is a minor version, released on the above schedule of approximately every 6 months, in which the 1- or 2-digit number's parity indicates the type of release: if *xx* is even (e.g.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] 3.20) the release is considered stable, whereas if *xx* is odd, it represents a current development snapshot (e.g.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] 3.21) that will eventually evolve into the next stable release.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] 3.20.6; these are made on a frequency of weeks in order to fix issues, add non-breaking enhancements, etc.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 40 started a new versioning scheme in which a single number is incremented with each semi-annual release.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The number is followed by a dot and then "alpha", "beta", or "rc" for a development release, or a decimal for a minor stable release (much like the *yy* mentioned previously).
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME releases are made to the main FTP server in the form of source code with configure scripts, which are compiled by operating system vendors and integrated with the rest of their systems before distribution.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Most vendors only use stable and tested versions of GNOME and provide it in the form of easily installed, pre-compiled packages.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The source code of every stable and development version of GNOME is stored in the GNOME git source code repository.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] A number of build scripts (such as JHBuild or formerly GARNOME) are available to help automate the process of compiling the source code.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Since the introduction of Discourse forum in 2019, the discussion moved from mailing lists and in October 2022, the project announced the plan to close all its public mailing lists.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME developers and users gather at an annual GUADEC meeting to discuss the current state and the future direction of GNOME.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME incorporates standards and programs from freedesktop.org to better support interoperability with other desktops.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME is mainly written in C, XML, C++, C#, HTML, Vala, Python, JavaScript, CSS, and more.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] A number of language bindings are available.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The GLib data structures and utilities library, GObject object and type system and GTK widget toolkit along with the Adwaita design language implemented by libadwaita, comprise the central part of the GNOME development platform.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] The GNOME desktop environment does not consist solely of the graphical control element library GTK and the core applications that make use of it.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] There are quite a few additional software packages that make up the GNOME desktop environment, such as the above.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Wayland support was introduced in GNOME 3.10 and deemed "for the majority of users […] a usable day to day experience" by 3.20, at which point Wayland became the default user session.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] With GNOME 3.24, Wayland compatibility was extended to Nvidia drivers.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] In GNOME 3.30 or later, it was possible to run GNOME without X11 running at startup, using only Wayland.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] In GNOME 50, using the X11 session in Mutter is no longer possible, and GNOME became one of the first desktop environments to only support Wayland.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] X11 applications can still be run though XWayland.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] In May 2011 Lennart Poettering proposed systemd as a GNOME dependency.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] As systemd is available only on Linux, the proposal led to a discussion of possibly dropping support for other platforms in future GNOME releases.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Since GNOME 3.2, multiseat support has only been available on systems using systemd.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] In November 2012 the GNOME release team concluded there will be no compile time dependency on systemd for basic functionality, like session tracking.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] For non-basic functionality, like power management, compile time dependency is possible.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] For example, there is no concept of systemd inhibitors in alternatives like consolekit.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] A package manager may want to ensure that the system is not turned off while the upgrade is taking place.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Since GNOME 49 systemd became a stronger dependency.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p01] Adrian Vovk had announced two major changes: GDM is gaining a dependency on systemd’s userdb infrastructure and the builtin service manager of gnome-session is being removed.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] GNOME OS is an operating system designed to provide a streamlined, container-centric platform that serves as both an experimental testbed and a showcase for GNOME's user interface and application ecosystem.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] Unlike many Linux distributions, GNOME OS is not based on other distributions such as Arch Linux, Debian, or Fedora Linux.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] It is built from the ground up using tools like BuildStream, Freedesktop SDK, and GNOME Build Meta, ensuring a clean and consistent environment tailored for GNOME development.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] This approach allows GNOME OS to provide a standardized platform for developers to develop the latest GNOME software without the variability introduced by other distributions.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] While GNOME OS shares similarities with immutable distributions like Fedora Silverblue, it remains distinct in its purpose and design, focusing solely on the GNOME ecosystem.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] The concept of GNOME OS began to take shape around 2010, with discussions and planning sessions focused on creating a more unified and cohesive system for GNOME.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] The vision was inspired by other platforms like Android, WebOS, and MeeGo, with the goal of designing an operating system that could offer a better experience for both users and developers.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] In 2012, during the GUADEC conference held in A Coruña, a significant planning session, known as a Birds of a Feather (BoF) session, was conducted on July 30.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] This session brought together key members of the GNOME community to discuss and plan the future direction of GNOME OS.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] The discussions covered several critical areas, including application development, testing, core user experience (UX), pattern language, and support for touch and mobile devices.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] Early OSTree-based build efforts were sometimes informally referred to as "**gnome-ostree**", but the continuous integration pipeline that emerged became known as **GNOME Continuous**, reflecting its primary role as a continuous integration and testing platform for GNOME.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] It was designed to provide a rolling-release environment where developers could test GNOME 3.x features and applications in isolation.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] Technologically, GNOME Continuous adopted OSTree for atomic updates, allowing the system to roll back to previous states if updates failed, ensuring system stability.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] This technology was later popularized by Fedora Silverblue and other immutable Linux distributions.
[src:fedora-linux/gnome-p02] GNOME OS first became publicly visible as a testable reference platform around 2020, when the project published a “GNOME OS Nightly” page offering downloadable images and instructions for running the system in virtual machines or on real hardware.
[src:fedora-linux/ostree] It operates on commits which refer to filesystem trees.
[src:fedora-linux/ostree] To refer to different commits while maintaining a user-readable name, OSTree provides "references" (analogous to branches in Git), such as `exampleos/buildmain/x86_64-runtime`.
[src:fedora-linux/ostree] Files provided by commits are by default immutable, done by mounting the filesystem itself as read-only.
[src:fedora-linux/ostree] OSTree allows for two mutable directories for storing user data: `/etc` and `/var`.
[src:fedora-linux/ostree] It provides a mechanism to allow filesystem trees to add configuration files to `/etc` while also allowing system administrators to edit those files in a persistent manner.
[src:fedora-linux/ostree] OSTree provides bootloader management for hardware deployments.
[src:fedora-linux/ostree] This enables atomic updates, as OSTree can create deployments and atomically insert them into the boot partition.
[src:fedora-linux/ostree] It also allows for systemwide rollback by selecting old deployments during startup.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat has become associated to a large extent with its enterprise operating system Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL).
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Having grown significantly beyond just Linux, it also includes the OpenShift Container Platform, Ansible Automation Platform, and Red Hat AI.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat had acquired the open-source enterprise middleware vendor JBoss.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat now offers OpenShift Virtualization, which replaces the long retired product Red Hat Virtualization (RHV), an enterprise virtualization product.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat provides operating system platforms, middleware, applications, management products, support, training, and consulting services.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat creates, maintains, and contributes to many free software projects.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] It has acquired the codebases of several proprietary software products through corporate mergers and acquisitions, and has released such software under open source licenses.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] As of June 2026, Red Hat is the fourth largest corporate contributor to the Linux kernel after Intel, Meta, and Google.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On October 28, 2018, IBM announced its intent to acquire Red Hat for $34 billion.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] It now operates as an independent subsidiary.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Effective January 12, 2026 Red Hat converted (legal process known as "conversion") from a corporation and as Red Hat, Inc. to then be a limited liability company with new formal name Red Hat, LLC.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In 1993, Bob Young incorporated the ACC Corporation, a catalog business that sold Linux and Unix software accessories.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In 1994, Marc Ewing created his own Linux distribution, which he named Red Hat Linux (associated with the time Ewing wore a red Cornell University lacrosse hat, given to him by his grandfather, while attending Carnegie Mellon University).
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Ewing released the software in October, and it became known as the Halloween release.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Young bought Ewing's business in 1995, and the two merged to become Red Hat Software, with Young serving as chief executive officer (CEO).
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat went public on August 11, 1999, achieving—at the time—the eighth-biggest first-day gain in the history of Wall Street.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Matthew Szulik succeeded Bob Young as CEO in December of that year.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Bob Young went on to found the online print on demand and self-publishing company, Lulu in 2002.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On November 15, 1999, Red Hat acquired Cygnus Solutions.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Cygnus provided commercial support for free software and housed maintainers of GNU software products such as the GNU Debugger and GNU Binutils.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] One of the founders of Cygnus, Michael Tiemann, became the chief technical officer of Red Hat and by 2008 the vice president of open-source affairs.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Later Red Hat acquired WireSpeed, C2Net, Hell's Kitchen Systems, and Akopia.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In February 2000, *InfoWorld* awarded Red Hat its fourth consecutive "Operating System Product of the Year" award for Red Hat Linux 6.1.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat acquired Planning Technologies, Inc. in 2001 and AOL's iPlanet directory and certificate-server software in 2004.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat moved its headquarters from Durham to North Carolina State University's Centennial Campus in Raleigh, North Carolina in February 2002.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In the following month Red Hat introduced Red Hat Linux Advanced Server, later renamed Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL).
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Dell, IBM, HP and Oracle Corporation announced their support of the platform.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In December 2005, *CIO Insight* magazine conducted its annual "Vendor Value Survey", in which Red Hat ranked #1 in value for the second year in a row.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat stock became part of the NASDAQ-100 on December 19, 2005.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat acquired open-source middleware provider JBoss on June 5, 2006, and JBoss became a division of Red Hat.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On September 18, 2006, Red Hat released the Red Hat Application Stack, which integrated the JBoss technology and which was certified by other well-known software vendors.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On December 12, 2006, Red Hat stock moved from trading on NASDAQ (RHAT) to the New York Stock Exchange (RHT).
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In 2007 Red Hat acquired MetaMatrix and made an agreement with Exadel to distribute its software.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On March 15, 2007, Red Hat released Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5, and in June acquired Mobicents.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On March 13, 2008, Red Hat acquired Amentra, a provider of systems integration services for service-oriented architecture, business process management, systems development, and enterprise data services.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On July 27, 2009, Red Hat replaced CIT Group in Standard and Poor's 500 stock index, a diversified index of 500 leading companies of the U.S. economy.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] This was reported as a major milestone for Linux.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On December 15, 2009, it was reported that Red Hat would pay US$8.8 million to settle a class action lawsuit related to the restatement of financial results from July 2004.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] District Court for the Eastern District of North Carolina.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat reached the proposed settlement agreement and recorded a one-time charge of US$8.8 million for the quarter that ended Nov.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On January 10, 2011, Red Hat announced that it would expand its headquarters in two phases, adding 540 employees to the Raleigh operation, and investing over US$109 million.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The state of North Carolina is offering up to US$15 million in incentives.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The second phase involves "expansion into new technologies such as software virtualization and technology cloud offerings".
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On August 25, 2011, Red Hat announced it would move about 600 employees from the N.C.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] State Centennial Campus to the Two Progress Plaza building.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] A ribbon cutting ceremony was held on June 24, 2013, in the re-branded Red Hat Headquarters.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In 2012, Red Hat became the first one-billion dollar open-source company, reaching US$1.13 billion in annual revenue during its fiscal year.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat passed the $2 billion benchmark in 2015.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] As of February 2018 the company's annual revenue was nearly $3 billion.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On October 16, 2015, Red Hat announced its acquisition of IT automation startup Ansible, rumored for an estimated US$100 million.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In June 2017, Red Hat announced Red Hat Hyperconverged Infrastructure (RHHI) 1.0 software product.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On October 28, 2018, IBM announced its intent to acquire Red Hat for US$34 billion, in one of its largest-ever acquisitions.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The company will operate out of IBM's Hybrid Cloud division.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Microsoft, Amazon, and Google reportedly also considered buying Red Hat.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Six months later, on May 3, 2019, the US Department of Justice concluded its review of IBM's proposed Red Hat acquisition, and according to Steven J.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Vaughan-Nichols "essentially approved the IBM/Red Hat deal".
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The acquisition was closed on July 9, 2019.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat is the primary sponsor of the Fedora Project, a community-supported free software project that aims to promote the rapid progress of free and open-source software and content.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat operates on a business model based on open-source software, development within a community, professional quality assurance, and subscription-based customer support.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] They produce open-source code so that more programmers can make adaptations and improvements.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat sells subscriptions for the support, training, and integration services that help customers in using their open-source software products.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Customers pay one set price for unlimited access to services such as Red Hat Network and up to 24/7 support.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In September 2014, however, CEO Jim Whitehurst announced that Red Hat was "in the midst of a major shift from client-server to cloud-mobile".
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Rich Bynum, a member of Red Hat's legal team, attributes Linux's success and rapid development partially to open-source business models, including Red Hat's.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat's links to branches of Israel's military and statements of support for Israeli associates has also led to some controversy and calls for boycott during the ongoing conflict in Gaza.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Air Force and US Department of Defense supplier, working closely with Lockheed Martin on warfare-related AI capabilities.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In 2026, a brochure titled "Compress the kill cycle with Red Hat Device Edge" surfaced, but it was promptly removed from Red Hat websites.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat engineers worked with the One Laptop per Child initiative (a non-profit organization established by members of the MIT Media Lab) to design and produce an inexpensive laptop and try to provide every child in the world with access to open communication, open knowledge, and open learning.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The XO-4 laptop, the last machine the project produced (in 2012), runs a slimmed-down version of Fedora 17 as its operating system.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Avi Kivity began the development of KVM in mid-2006 at Qumranet, a technology startup company that was acquired by Red Hat in 2008.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat is the largest contributor to the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] It has several employees working full-time on Evolution, the official personal information manager for GNOME.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Init system and system/service manager for Linux systems.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Network-capable sound server program distributed via the freedesktop.org project.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Dogtail, an open-source automated graphical user interface (GUI) test framework initially developed by Red Hat, consists of free software released under the GNU General Public License (GPL) and is written in Python.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] It allows developers to build and test their applications.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat announced the release of Dogtail at the 2006 Red Hat Summit.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat MRG is a clustering product intended for integrated high-performance computing (HPC).
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The acronym MRG stands for "Messaging Realtime Grid".
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] As of 2011, Red Hat works with the Condor High-Throughput Computing System community and also provides support for the software.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The Tuna performance-monitoring tool runs in the MRG environment.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat produced the online publication Opensource.com since January 20, 2010.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The site highlights ways open-source principles apply in domains other than software development.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The site tracks the application of open-source philosophy to business, education, government, law, health, and life.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The company originally produced a newsletter called Under the Brim.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Wide Open magazine first appeared in March 2004, as a means for Red Hat to share technical content with subscribers regularly.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The Under the Brim newsletter and Wide Open magazine merged in November 2004, to become *Red Hat Magazine*.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In January 2010, *Red Hat Magazine* became Opensource.com.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In April 2023 Red Hat went through company layoffs and laid off the team maintaining Opensource.com.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In 2007, Red Hat announced that it had reached an agreement with some free software and open-source (FOSS) companies that allowed it to make a distribution portal called Red Hat Exchange, reselling FOSS software with the original branding intact.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] However, by 2010, Red Hat had abandoned the Exchange program to focus their efforts more on their Open Source Channel Alliance which began in April 2009.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat build of Keycloak (formerly known as Red Hat Single Sign-On) is a software product to allow single sign-on with Identity Management and Access Management aimed at modern applications and services.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] It is based on the open-source project Keycloak, which acts as an upstream project.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat Subscription Management (RHSM) combines content delivery with subscription management.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat is the largest contributor to the Ceph Storage SDS project : Block, File & Object Storage which runs on industry-standard x86 servers and Ethernet IP as well as ARM, InfiniBand, and other technologies.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Ceph aims primarily for completely distributed operation without a single point of failure, scalable to the exabyte level.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Ceph replicates data and makes it fault-tolerant, using commodity hardware and requiring no specific hardware support.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Ceph's system offers disaster recovery and data redundancy through techniques such as replication, erasure coding, snapshots and storage cloning.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] As a result of its design, the system is both self-healing and self-managing, aiming to minimize administration time and other costs.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In this way, administrators have a single, consolidated system that avoids silos and collects the storage within a common management framework.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Ceph consolidates several storage use cases and improves resource utilization.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] It also lets an organization deploy servers where needed.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat operates OpenShift, a cloud computing platform as a service, supporting applications written in Node.js, PHP, Perl, Python, Ruby, JavaEE and more.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On July 31, 2018, Red Hat announced the release of Istio 1.0, a microservices management program used in tandem with the Kubernetes platform.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The software purports to provide "traffic management, service identity and security, policy enforcement and telemetry" services in order to streamline Kubernetes use under the various Fedora-based operating systems.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat's Brian Redbeard Harring described Istio as "aiming to be a control plane, similar to the Kubernetes control plane, for configuring a series of proxy servers that get injected between application components".
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Also Red Hat is the second largest contributor to Kubernetes code itself, after Google.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat markets a version of OpenStack which helps manage a data center in the manner of cloud computing.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat CloudForms provides management of virtual machines, instances and containers based on VMware vSphere, Red Hat Virtualization, Microsoft Hyper-V, OpenStack, Amazon EC2, Google Cloud Platform, Microsoft Azure, and Red Hat OpenShift.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] CloudForms is based on the ManageIQ project that Red Hat open sourced.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Code in ManageIQ is from the over US$100 million acquisition of ManageIQ in 2012.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Container Linux (formerly CoreOS Linux) is a discontinued open-source lightweight operating system based on the Linux kernel and designed for providing infrastructure to clustered deployments.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] As an operating system, Container Linux provided only the minimal functionality required for deploying applications inside software containers, together with built-in mechanisms for service discovery and configuration sharing.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat contributed, with several software developers, to LibreOffice, a free and open-source office suite.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] However, in 2023, Red Hat announced they were not going to include LibreOffice in RHEL 10, citing the ability to download LibreOffice from Flatpak on RHEL desktops.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat also organises "Open Source Day" events where multiple partners show their open-source technologies.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat was one of the largest contributors to the X Window System.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Started in 2008, by Red Hat developer Kristian Høgsberg, with the aim of replacing the X Windows System.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Over and above Red Hat's major products and acquisitions, Red Hat programmers have produced software programming-tools and utilities to supplement standard Unix and Linux software.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Some of these Red Hat "products" have found their way from specifically Red Hat operating environments via open-source channels to a wider community.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The Red Hat website lists the organization's major involvements in free and open-source software projects.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat Czech s.r.o. is a research and development arm of Red Hat, based in Brno, Czech Republic.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The subsidiary was formed in 2006 and has 1,180 employees (2019).
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat chose to enter the Czech Republic in 2006 over other locations due to the country's embrace of open-source.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The subsidiary expanded in 2017 to a second location in the Brno Technology Park to accommodate an additional 350 employees.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In 2016, Red Hat Czech reported revenue of CZK 1,002 million (FY 2016), and net income of CZK 123 million (FY 2016), with assets of CZK 420 million (FY 2016)|CZK 325 million (FY 2015).
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The group was named the "Most progressive employer of the year" in the Czech Republic in 2010, and the "Best Employer in the Czech Republic" for large scale companies in 2011 by Aon.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In 2000, Red Hat created the subsidiary **Red Hat India** to deliver Red Hat software, support, and services to Indian customers.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] As of today (2025 December) 1800 employees work for Red Hat India.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Colin Tenwick, former vice president and general manager of Red Hat EMEA, said Red Hat India was opened "in response to the rapid adoption of Red Hat Linux in the subcontinent.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Demand for open-source solutions from the Indian markets is rising and Red Hat wants to play a major role in this region." Red Hat India has worked with local companies to enable the adoption of open-source technology in both government and education.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] In 2006, Red Hat India had a distribution network of more than 70 channel partners spanning 27 cities across India.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat India's channel partners included MarkCraft Solutions, Ashtech Infotech Pvt Ltd., Efensys Technologies, Embee Software, Allied Digital Services, and Softcell Technologies.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Distributors include Integra Micro Systems and Ingram Micro.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat's first major acquisition involved Delix Computer GmbH-Linux Div, the Linux-based operating-system division of Delix Computer, a German computer company, on July 30, 1999.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat acquired Cygnus Solutions, a company that provided commercial support for free software, on January 11, 2000 – it was the company's largest acquisition, for US$674 million.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Michael Tiemann, co-founder of Cygnus, served as the chief technical officer of Red Hat after the acquisition.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Red Hat made the most acquisitions in 2000 with five: Cygnus Solutions, Bluecurve, Wirespeed Communications, Hell's Kitchen Systems, and C2Net.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On June 5, 2006, Red Hat acquired open-source middleware provider JBoss for US$420 million and integrated it as its own division of Red Hat.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] On December 14, 1998, Red Hat made its first divestment, when Intel and Netscape acquired undisclosed minority stakes in the company.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] The next year, on March 9, 1999, Compaq, IBM, Dell and Novell each acquired undisclosed minority stakes in Red Hat.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Netscape Security-Certain Asts was acquired from Netscape Security Solutions.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Intel Corporation acquired a minority stake in Red Hat.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] Compaq acquired a minority stake in Red Hat.
[src:fedora-linux/red-hat] IBM acquired a minority stake in Red Hat.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Although it was created for use in Red Hat Linux, RPM is now used in many Linux distributions such as PCLinuxOS, Fedora Linux, AlmaLinux, CentOS, openSUSE, OpenMandriva and Oracle Linux.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] It has also been ported to some other operating systems, such as Novell NetWare (as of version 6.5 SP3), IBM's AIX (as of version 4), IBM i, and ArcaOS.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] An RPM package can contain an arbitrary set of files.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Most RPM files are "binary RPMs" (or BRPMs) containing the compiled version of some software.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] There are also "source RPMs" (or SRPMs) containing the source code used to build a binary package.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] These have an appropriate tag in the file header that distinguishes them from normal (B)RPMs, causing them to be extracted to /usr/src on installation.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] SRPMs customarily carry the file extension ".src.rpm" (.spm on file systems limited to 3 extension characters, e.g. old DOS FAT).
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] RPM was originally written in 1997 by Erik Troan and Marc Ewing, based on `pms`, `rpp`, and `pm` experiences.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] `pm` was written by Rik Faith and Doug Hoffman in May 1995 for Red Hat Software, its design and implementations were influenced greatly by `pms`, a package management system by Faith and Kevin Martin in the fall of 1993 for the Bogus Linux Distribution.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] `pm` preserves the "Pristine Sources + patches" paradigm of `pms`, while adding features and eliminating arbitrary limitations present in the implementation.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] `pm` provides greatly enhanced database support for tracking and verifying installed packages.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Packages may come from within a particular distribution (for example Red Hat Enterprise Linux) or be built for it by other parties (for example RPM Fusion for Fedora Linux).
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Circular dependencies among mutually dependent RPMs (so-called "dependency hell") can be problematic; in such cases a single installation command needs to specify all the relevant packages.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] RPMs are often collected centrally in one or more repositories on the internet.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] A site often has its own RPM repositories which may either act as local mirrors of such internet repositories or be locally maintained collections of useful RPMs.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Several front-ends to RPM ease the process of obtaining and installing RPMs from repositories and help in resolving their dependencies.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Working behind the scenes of the package manager is the RPM database, stored in `/var/lib/rpm`.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] It consists of a single database (`Packages`) containing all of the meta information of the installed RPMs.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Multiple databases are created for indexing purposes, replicating data to speed up queries.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] The database is used to keep track of all files that are changed and created when a user (using RPM) installs a package, thus enabling the user (via RPM) to reverse the changes and remove the package later.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] If the database gets corrupted (which is possible if the RPM client is killed), the index databases can be recreated with the `rpm --rebuilddb` command.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Whilst the RPM format is the same across different Linux distributions, the detailed conventions and guidelines may vary across them.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] RPMs with the `noarch.rpm` extension do not depend on a particular CPU architecture.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] For example, these RPMs may contain graphics and text for other programs to use.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] They may also contain shell scripts or programs written in other interpreted programming languages such as Python.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] The package label fields do not need to match the filename.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Libraries are distributed in two separate packages for each version.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] One contains the precompiled code for use at run-time, while the second one contains the related development files such as headers, etc.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Those packages have "-devel" appended to their name field.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] The system administrator should ensure that the versions of the binary and development packages match.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] The "Recipe" for creating an RPM package is a spec file.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Spec files end in the ".spec" suffix and contain the package name, version, RPM revision number, steps to build, install, and clean a package, and a changelog.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Multiple packages can be built from a single RPM spec file, if desired.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] RPM packages are created from RPM spec files using the rpmbuild tool.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Spec files are usually distributed within SRPM files, which contain the spec file packaged along with the source code.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] A typical RPM is pre-compiled software ready for direct installation.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] The corresponding source code can also be distributed.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] This is done in an SRPM, which also includes the "SPEC" file describing the software and how it is built.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] The SRPM also allows the user to compile, and perhaps modify, the code itself.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] A software package could contain only platform independent scripts.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] In such a case, the developer could provide only an SRPM, which is still an installable RPM.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] It contains "SPEC" file and optionally patches, but does not include sources (usually because of license).
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] As of June 2010, there are two versions of RPM in development: one led by the Fedora Project and Red Hat, and the other by a separate group led by a previous maintainer of RPM, a former employee of Red Hat.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] The *rpm.org* community's first major code revision was in July 2007; version 4.8 was released in January 2010, version 4.9 in March 2011, 4.10 in May 2012, 4.11 in January 2013, 4.12 in September 2014 and 4.13 in July 2015.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] This version is used by distributions such as Fedora Linux, Red Hat Enterprise Linux and derivatives, openSUSE, SUSE Linux Enterprise, Unity Linux, Mageia, OpenEmbedded, Tizen and OpenMandriva Lx (formerly Mandriva).
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] Jeff Johnson, the RPM maintainer since 1999, continued development efforts together with participants from several other distributions.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] This version was used by distributions such as Wind River Linux (until Wind River Linux 10), Rosa Linux, and OpenMandriva Lx (former Mandriva Linux which switched to rpm5 in 2011) and also by the OpenPKG project which provides packages for other common UNIX-platforms.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] OpenMandriva Lx has switched back to rpm.org for 4.0 release.
[src:fedora-linux/rpm-package-manager] OpenEmbedded, the last major user of RPM5, switched back to rpm.org due to issues in RPM5.
